If you don't want to use SFML or any other graphics library, you can create a simple overlay menu for games using standard C++ and console output. Here's a basic example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

enum class MenuOption {
    Play,
    Options,
    Quit
};

MenuOption displayMenu() {
    std::cout << "=== Game Menu ===" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "1. Play" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "2. Options" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "3. Quit" << std::endl;

    int choice;
    std::cout << "Enter your choice (1-3): ";
    std::cin >> choice;

    switch(choice) {
        case 1:
            return MenuOption::Play;
        case 2:
            return MenuOption::Options;
        case 3:
            return MenuOption::Quit;
        default:
            std::cout << "Invalid choice. Please try again." << std::endl;
            return displayMenu(); // Recursive call if choice is invalid
    }
}

int main() {
    MenuOption chosenOption = displayMenu();

    switch(chosenOption) {
        case MenuOption::Play:
            std::cout << "Starting the game..." << std::endl;
            break;
        case MenuOption::Options:
            std::cout << "Opening options menu..." << std::endl;
            break;
        case MenuOption::Quit:
            std::cout << "Quitting the game..." << std::endl;
            break;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This example creates a simple text-based menu using console output. The `displayMenu` function displays the menu options and prompts the user for input. After the user makes a choice, the chosen option is returned and processed in the `main` function.

Keep in mind that this approach is limited in terms of visual presentation and interactivity compared to using dedicated graphics libraries like SFML. If you need more advanced or visually appealing menus, you may want to consider using a graphics library that suits your specific requirements.
